send you to the bottom of the food chain. Less than scum. He mumbles a complaint into his glass and wonders what changed.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Skill: Third Eye - Activated&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I've never been to a play before," Colin admits.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Excuse me if this is rude to assume, but can you read?" Rachel asks with a teasing smile. She's twisting one of Colin's short blonde locks in her fingers.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Ay, I can read," Colin chuckles, "Why do you ask?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Well Master Colin," Rachel teases again, I knew they would get along, "The library here has a fair share of scripts available to read."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"To... read?" Colin looks confused, "Like- the same thing the actors read?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Ay," Rachel says, perfectly mimicking his accent, "Why don't we see if we can borrow a copy for you to take home?" Colin's face brightens, the thought of reading a fine piece of culture bringing light to his days on the farm.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I'd appreciate that very much," Colin says.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Skill: Third Eye - Deactivated&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I climb the steps to the room. Knocking three times on the door before letting myself in. "Colin, my boy," I place my hands on my hips, "I'm afraid you're staying here for the time being."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Excuse me?" Colin asks, a mortified expression on his face.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Yes, your father didn't think to bring any coin for this excursion," I sigh as solemn as I can muster, "Effective immediately, you're under my care. At least until you work off your debt."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Rachel scoffs, "Marina, please be-"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Colin jumps in, "So I'm not going back to the farm?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Afraid not," I say with a smile. Colin smiles back at me. Rachel looks on confused. "Finish up with Miss Rachel and I'll show you the ropes."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr /&gt; &lt;p&gt;"So... oopsie poopsie," the white, featureless, generic humanoid figure said with a shrug.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Oopsie... poopsie?" I stare confused.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Oh, sorry, were you not listening?" The figure tilts its head.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"No, I was listening, I'm dead?" I try to get a confirmation.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Yes, and that's on us- well, me," the figure wrings its hands anxiously.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"And that's why I'm-" I look down at my white featureless arms and the black star filled void that surrounds us, "I'm going to heaven?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"If you want," the figure emotes like it is thinking, then a book appears in the void. Leather bound and aged tan pages, the figure takes a finger and drags it down the page and reads a list to itself. "Looking at your history, you have a lot of regrets. Complex ones."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I nod, grimacing at the things left behind in my closet. The friends I made online that will never hear from me again. The person I was supposed to become, it's gone forever.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"How about this," the figure closes the books swiftly, "A win-win for both of us. You get the life you always wanted, and my brothers get off my back."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"The life-" I try to remember the life that I had. It wasn't much. Spent inside, hating myself, hating the world for hating me, and then making me hate myself more. "What does that entail?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Well, new name, new body, new life, a whole new world, if you wanted?" The figure folds its arm, excited that I may take up its proposal.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Yeah," I say.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In a flurry, a series of bodies fill the void around me. "Take your pick," the figure smiles. Or at least, it appears to try to smile.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There's one about my height, evenly chested, feminine, wide hips. I point to it. With a nod, the body becomes mine. "A splendid choice, very attractive in almost any time, what about-"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Could I make a change?" I ask, "To the body."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Sure, it's the least I can do," the figure tries to smile again, "What did you want?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I want a penis," I say confidently.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Done," the figure says. I look down and see an average member between my legs.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"You don't want to-" I start to ask, but the void changes before my eyes. The bodies have been replaced with mirrors that look into a variety of worlds. Medieval, futuristic, cyberpunk.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Sorry, you were saying something?" The figure tilts its head quizzically.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"You're fine with giving me this body?" I ask.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It shrugs, "It's your life."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I peer into a mirror that shows me a world on the cusp of innovation. Streets are filled with mud, wagons drawn by horses march alongside vehicles that run on smokeless engines. "Tell me more about this one."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The figure peers over my shoulder, "Ah yes, think Industrial Revolution meets tabletop role playing game." It looks pleased with the description.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Yeah, that works," I say then pause, "What are you? What is all this?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Didn't I say? I'm the goddess of death," the figure looks proud of herself.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"And this is-" She cuts me off.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Your second chance at life, remember? Oopsie poopsie?" She looks at me expectantly, "This is the world you would like, yes?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;When I nod, the figure transforms into a beautiful woman, victorian style dress, and a cloud of black smog covers her face. "Wonderful," she sighs, "Now are you ready?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"This is a lot like those-" I start to say but she cuts me off again.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I forgot, your skills!" She summons a user interface in front of her, swiping around sliders and then pressing a button. An interface appears before me with a keyboard.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;Enter your name:&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;M-A-R-I-N-A S-M-I-T-H&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;Select your skills:&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;A giant list of skills begins to generate in the interface. A second chance at life. I can be anything I want. "Goddess, are these the only skills I can get?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She ponders for a moment, "Interesting proposal. I like it. Yes, if you gain enough experience, you may inherit new skills."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"And how do I gain experience?" I ask. Please don't let it be fighting monsters.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Fine, not by fighting monsters, how about through interactions?" The goddess suggests.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"You can hear my-" she cuts me off.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Marina, you currently exist in my domain," she laughs a haughty laugh, "I am everything." Her words echo through the void.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Scary. No offense.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"None taken," she swipes through the interface in front of her, "There, no need to fight pesky monsters to gain experience."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I scroll through the skills. The first that speaks to me reads "Assess."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;blockquote&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;Assess: Gain insight into the thoughts, preferences, alliances, and abilities of an individual. &lt;i&gt;Can be upgraded.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/blockquote&gt; &lt;p&gt;I select it. I continue to scroll, but nothing-&lt;/p&gt; &lt;blockquote&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;Insightful: Gain experience at an accelerated rate. &lt;i&gt;Can be upgraded.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/blockquote&gt; &lt;p&gt;I'd be a fool not to take that one. The interface updates, 0 skill points remaining.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Wonderful, absolutely splendid," the goddess seems uninterested suddenly, "Now, would you like to be reincarnated or shall I splice you into the world."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I look at the interface. My two options are "Select age" and "Reincarnate", reincarnation would be nice. A total do-over. A chance to do things right the first time.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I'll be honest with you, people don't learn from their mistakes easily," the goddess admits.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Which is to say?" I challenge.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Nothing, only that the last time I reincarnated someone they ended up the same asshole they were the first time," she shrugs, "They got better at justifying it."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"No karma system then?" I joke.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"He experienced his share of hardship," the goddess says, an air of remorse surrounds the conversation.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Let's do it," I say. I press the button labeled "Reincarnation".&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"If you wish," the goddess seems unimpressed.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"When will I see you again?" I ask.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The goddess gives a bashful laugh, "Oh don't worry, I'll see you soon enough." She raises her fingers to snap them, "But until then, why don't you try to enjoy your new life?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;SNAP&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I open my eyes and stare at the two people leaning over me. A man and a woman. They're fucking huge.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;They say something to me but I can't- They speak a different language?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Marina," I perk up at the mention of my chosen name. They talk amongst themselves before the man takes me and lifts me into the air. "Marina," he says again, a smile grows across his face. I may as well smile back at him.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He's a tall man. He must be dad. Then the woman must be mom. I try to speak but gibberish comes out. They're amazed. A woman in a white dress with a hat adorned with a red cross begins talking to my mom. The woman is concerned, or confused. Mom looks to me with a similar confused look. Oh right, babies cry.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;As I let out a wail, my dad brings me to his chest, rubbing my head softly. He's warm. I reach for my mom. She reaches back for me. Dad begrudgingly hands me over. Sorry, Dad, we'll have plenty of time together.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr /&gt; &lt;p&gt;The market is busy today. There aren't any special holidays this time of year, it could always be that it is a nice spring day and everyone is enjoying their day off. "Miss Marina, look at this," Colin calls for me.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Colin, for the last time, if you call me 'Miss' again, you're going to give me the impression that I'm some old hag," I say with a teasing wink to the lady running the flower stand.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Doing something special for the girls today, Marina?" The lady asks.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I nod, I try to get the girls flowers when I can. It was easier to do when there was only a handful of them. Now I have to budget much more sparingly.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Yes, if I could get-" I pat my pockets looking for my list of everyone's favorites. It's empty. I check my apron, a light tan thick cotton thing with leather straps, nothing there either. "Well... crap," I say. The lady laughs.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Marina, please," she begins absentmindedly picking out the flowers from the bins surrounding her booth, "I may be old, but I remember all my customer's orders."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Very impressive," I say, then with a teasing lilt, "If you ever want to pivot careers, I might have an opening for you."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She chortles, "Please, as if you have any need for a real hag in your bar."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"All the same, come by sometime, let my girls pamper you. It's about time you took credit for your amazing work," I hand her a small leather pouch with too much coin in it. My bar stays in good community standing by expertly over paying at the right times. I learned pretty early on that this move is viewed as crass and "infringes on one's honor as a-" blah blah blah. Too much coin at the wrong time could end me up on the wrong side of a flintlock.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Marina," she starts to object, but I put my hand on her’s before she can reject the offer, "Fine, one drink, that's all you're getting out of me."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Good to see you again," I say and carefully hand off the flowers to Colin.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Marina," Colin says from behind dozens of bouquets, "Could I..."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I look around at the stalls to try and deduce what it was Colin wanted. Then I spot it, a merchant surrounded by shelves of books, sitting on a stool depressed at the pitiful amount of sales he has achieved.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Good afternoon," I say politely, "Mind if we have a look at your wares?" The book seller looks up excited and nods. He points to me then to Colin. "Ay, for the boy," I respond. Quickly, the merchant gathers a small stack of books and splays them out on a table. He motions a description of each story, emoting like a dragon breathing fire, moving slowly and purposefully like an automaton, and carefully dancing on the rug that denotes his spot in the marketplace.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"What's wrong with him?" Colin asks.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Why don't you ask him?" I challenge.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Colin freezes, the merchant looking at him with eager eyes. "Uhm, the one with the dancing please," Colin says after a loud gulp.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The merchant claps his hands together, and wraps the book in a light tan paper, ties a string around it and hands it to Colin. I pull out a gold coin and hand it to the dancing man. When he tries to hand it back, I place it more forcefully into his palm. "Have you sold any other books today?" I ask.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He bites the inside of his cheek.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"If you need to justify it, think of it as an investment," I wrap his hand around the coin, "I'll see you next week, yes?" He nods confidently. If Colin stays strong against his father, I expect he will become good friends with this merchant.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Thank you," Colin says, "I've never owned a book before."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;What a shame. A kid like him that is eager to learn is hard to come by. This curiosity should be explored and encouraged. I'd hate to see it wither away on the vine should he decide to go back home.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"What do you say, Colin? Should we head back?" I say. He nods excitedly. I love where the bar ended up being put. The most ideal spot would have been right on the water, but that would be a selfish decision and expensive. Instead, I picked something off Main Street, close enough that a few signs could attract my first customers, and far enough away that I wasn't constantly being harassed by the police.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It was a shabby institution to start, it took me almost a decade to get my license to sell alcohol. If it wasn't for the girls I managed to pluck out of the street trash at the beginning, I wouldn't have made it. We turn onto the street with my bar and enter quietly. I doubt anyone would be awake yet, but if they were, they would certainly be hung over.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Where shall I put these?" Colin says, lifting the bouquets.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I grab the list of everyone's favorite flowers from the drawer next to the register. Taking a few of the bouquet's from Colin's arms, I hand him the list. "You're going to deliver them," I say with a warm smile.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"But everyone is asleep still, I don't want to wake them," Colin blushes. Such a shy boy, so easy to upset.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I'm sure Miss Rachel wouldn't mind being woken up with flowers, why don't we start there?" I suggest, trading the bundle of sunflowers I took for a bouquet of artistically arranged baby's breath and lilies.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I follow close behind Colin. He takes the steps to the second floor slowly. His emotional intelligence is quite high for a boy his age, it's nice to see. He knocks on the door once. I hear stirring from inside. Rachel opens the door, her robe barely on. "What do you want it's-" she starts to complain, but then she realizes who is at the door and what they are holding.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Sorry," Colin averts his gaze, a crush quickly developing, "I thought you would like some-"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Oh Colin," Rachel fixes her robe, "You shouldn't have, I'll cherish these forever!" She leans down and gives the boy a small kiss on the cheek.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"It's nothing, it was all-" I cut him off before he can spoil a good thing.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"It was Colin's idea, I helped bankroll it is all," I say with a hand on Colin's back. He nods, accepting this small white lie.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"I'm sure it was," Rachel says with a wink to Colin. Slowly more doors begin to open, girls looking to see if they received flowers from the sweet young boy. Colin is sure to check the list I gave him diligently.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"And for you, the baby's breath and..." Colin looks at the bouquets in his hands and looks confused.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"This one, right Colin?" I ask, handing the bouquet back to him.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Ay," he blushes.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Thank you, dear," says the tall blonde haired elf woman. Her name is Leeya, and she's the closest I have to a co-owner. At my lowest point, she took me in and got me back on my feet. "And thank you, Marina," Leeya winks at me.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I smile back at her warmly, "Come Colin, we have a few more to deliver." It's a short walk where we need to go, but it's one we do in silence. In Colin's arms is a single large bouquet left. All red roses.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I hold open the gate to the town cemetery for Colin, he shudders and makes a small religious gesture. "You only need to do that for a graveyard, boy," I say a bit too curtly.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Oh, is that not what this is?" He asks.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I shake my head, "This way."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Colin follows close behind, despite the kids of the cemetery owner frolicking around and playing games, it is an eerie atmosphere here. I point to a small collection of headstones. "Notice anything?" I ask.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Colin assesses the bland pieces of rock carefully, "No last names?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Meaning?" I prod.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"They were disowned, their family wanted nothing to do with them," he surmises almost correct.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Or..." I say waiting for him to think up the answer, "they were never claimed."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Who wouldn't claim their own kids?" Colin says with a depressed sigh. I take a flower from the bundle and place it on the first tombstone. As I kneel, Colin tries to object. "Miss- I mean, Marina, your clothes will get dirty," he tries to slide off his jacket and place it down, but he's too slow.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"This is Emaline," I trace the outline of her name with my finger. "She was..." Weird, I didn't feel this overcome with emotions the last time I was here. I wipe the tear pooling in my eye and stand back up. Taking the bundle from Colin's arms, I place a rose on each of the stones and take a moment of silence. When I let out a tired sigh, Colin wraps his arms around my shoulders. "What are you doing?" I ask with a chuckle.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Sorry, I should have asked," he wipes a tear from his own eyes, "I figured there's a sad reason they're all here, and it must be even sadder considering you're here."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Ay," I nod.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;We stand in the cemetery quietly.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Alright," I say, clapping a hand on Colin's shoulder, "Let's go open the bar, shall we?"&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
