      <title>Under Stagelights</title>
      <author> transcect </author>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/1339081/under-stagelights/</link>
      <comments>https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1339081-under-stagelights/chapter/1339092/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">01227ed7e92242a6e066ecdd6bbdc2daa0e2f103</guid>
      <pubDate>Fri, 20 Dec 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Adam has been learning the drums for two years. His teacher, the beautiful, fiery Sophie Summers, has a band of her own, and they're on the cusp of hitting the big time. But the night before their first big show, one where they can introduce themselves to the world, tragedy strikes and they find themselves down a member. To save the band, Sophie turns to Adam. But... there's a catch.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Under Stagelights is a lesbian egg fic.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1339081-under-stagelights/chapter/1339092/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Chapter 1: Lesbian Catnip&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;“Watch your sticking!” Adam tried to remember what pattern he’d hit the drums in, and with which hand. Two sixteenths on the snare with his left, one on the hi-tom with his right, and then the floor tom with his left? Or had it been right left right left? The crash had been with his right hand, he was sure of that.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Adam, the groove!” Fuck. Thinking too much. He tried to recover, syncing the kick up again, but it was too late. Sophie had stopped playing, and she was reaching over to her phone to cut the music. Adam scolded himself quietly, letting it get lost in the din. The music cut, guitar and bass disappearing, and Sophie, still sitting on a drum stool of her own, her own sticks clutched in one hand, turned to him, grinning.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Okay, that was my bad,” she said. “Should have told you the sticking bit later.” Adam shook his head. Sophie was hard to disappoint. For one, she was literally hard to disappoint, always passing along little compliments on his playing, even if he had stepped way out of the song by getting in his own head. &lt;em&gt;Yes, yes, just pretend ‘Talking in Your Sleep’ has a four quarter notes on the kick drum, a thumping four on the floor, because the rest was great! &lt;/em&gt;And even when Adam tried to brush it off, she’d roll her eyes and tell him to lighten up. And Adam would blush.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Because Sophie Summers, the beautiful, pixie cut red head, was hard to disappoint. Even if she wasn’t actually disappointed, and she was complimenting him on finding an interesting fill, Adam still struggled to not be &lt;em&gt;perfect &lt;/em&gt;for her. Charming, pretty, exceptionally talented girls deserved students who took their drumming as seriously as they did. And, sure, Adam hadn’t been playing as long, and he didn’t belong to a band like she did, and he certainly didn’t also double on bass, but he wanted to be better.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Tammy had teased that he would have quit drumming in the first year if he hadn’t been taught by Sophie. Adam had lied and said it wasn’t true. Whatever. It didn’t matter why he had stuck with it. It mattered that he had. And, even though he was still spending a lot of time messing up in front of Sophie, he was spending a lot more time getting good at drumming. Or, something close to it. Not ‘I should join a band good’, but ‘impress my friends with pencils’ good.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And, okay, friends was a strong word, too. There was Tammy, and that was pretty much it. Tammy, his roommate who had pseudo adopted him like a lost puppy off the street. They spent most evenings watching reruns of Seinfeld on the couch they had actually dragged in off the street, talking about how crazy it was that Julia Louise Dreyfus still looked the way she did. Tammy &lt;em&gt;was &lt;/em&gt;impressed by what Adam could drum out with a pencil, even if she did tease him with the requisite ‘and what does Sophie say?’ every time he pulled it out.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Tammy had been in a friend group with Adam’s older sister, Amy, and Amy had set them up as roommates when Adam had moved to D.C. Tammy, God bless her, had been immediately friendly to Adam. They were the only two people in the whole city from Bellway, Washington, she had said, and thus they must be friends. &lt;em&gt;Bellway, Washington to Beltway, Washington &lt;/em&gt;she had said.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You’re going to want to go right-left on the snare,” said Sophie, snapping Adam back. “Then, right on the hi-tom. Quick with that one, then left to the floor tom.” Sophie mimed the motion, and Adam nodded. He repeated the pattern, a little hesitation, and then did it again. Sophie nodded. “Good!”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I’ll mix it up again,” said Adam. Sophie rolled her eyes.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You’ll be fine.” She hit play on the song again, back to the start, two minutes before the fill that had tripped him up. They both jumped in.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Adam liked playing with Sophie. Playing side by side with another drummer was a bit like training wheels in a lot of ways. If he missed a note, Sophie would be playing the same one, and Adam could jump right back in. If he overplayed, Sophie, without missing a beat, would repeat the extra note on the next measure, and it would all seem like it was part of the song. And, if Adam completely fell away, she would start to riff and have fun and grin at him until he acquiesced and started playing again.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;They reached the fill and Adam, realizing it was coming, jumped a beat too early. Everything sounded loud and weird and noisy. Adam swore, Sophie laughed, and they both stopped playing, The Romantics still humming away in the speakers.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Do you want to do something else?” asked Sophie. Adam didn’t much care. He had been playing this song a lot over the last two weeks, trying to get it down. His timeframe for learning songs had shorted from being measured in months to weeks, but it was still a tiring process, especially if the song was tricky.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Sure,” he said.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Mind if we play some of mine?” asked Sophie. Adam shook his head.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Of course not,” he said. Sophie, drummer, writer, occasional singer for Shady Groove, a sort of alternative rock band, which Tammy had personally nicknamed “Lesbian Catnip”, liked to play her new stuff with Adam. They had gotten into the habit early on in his lessons, when Adam had trouble picking something to play. She said it helped her perfect the parts, teaching them to someone else. All of the odd bits stuck out that much more.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Adam liked it, too. He liked being a part of her process. He had joked that he ought to be included on all of the bands writing credits, and Sophie had seemed deadly serious about adding him until he begged her not to. He didn’t need to see his name down on the back of a CD.  She had only agreed when he had threatened to stop letting her play them with him. He was paying, after all.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Sophie grinned at him, her cheeks dimpling. Adam loved it when she smiled. When he had nailed something they had worked for a whole session on, finally getting the timing just perfect, and Sophie whooped and smiled and her cheeks dimpled, Adam thought he might genuinely be in love. Never mind that she was a lesbian, and fairly healthy part of Adam was pretty sure he was gay, or at least something like it. Maybe there was another kind of friendship, one just like the one he had with Tammy, just closer and happier and more lovely.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Instead of cueing a song, Sophie pulled a folder out of green backpack. Inside, there were sheets and sheets of handwritten notes. It had taken the full year for Adam to get accustomed to reading them. But he had, and as she settled it in front of him, Adam wiggled his sticks in the air.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Four on the floor,” he said.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Thought you might like that,” said Sophie, who settled her own drum sticks on her stool. Adam gave her a look. “I want to test the baseline, too!”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“In my lesson?” Adam was only teasing her, but Sophie frowned.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Sorry,” she said. “Sorry, no, you’re right.” She moved back towards the kit.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Sophie, I was kidding,” said Adam.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“No, no, I need to be teaching you drums, Adam,” she said. Adam gave her a look. She picked up her sticks, and Adam put his down.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Go get your bass,” he said. And Sophie shook her head again.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I always forget that you’re paying me,” she said. “This is my job. I can’t just… practice.” Adam opened his mouth to deny it. But, sometimes, when they were in the middle of a really good session, and Adam was just playing, he forgot that he was paying her, too.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Adam let it go. And Sophie started to describe the song that they were going to play. She walked him through the sticking, and Adam followed along, watching as she hit the drumheads, the ride, the hi-hat. She was so graceful with it. Her arms gathered themselves before they needed to be somewhere, getting out of their own way when they needed to, and they found their place. Adam still felt as though he was flailing about a little.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;They played for another half hour. It was a good song. Or, at least the drum part was fun, although that could be expected on a song written by a drummer. Sophie seemed pleased as they reached the end, and her face had dimpled again.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You like it?” she asked. Adam wondered if she knew that he couldn’t actually say &lt;em&gt;no &lt;/em&gt;to her. He nodded.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yes,” he said. “It’s really something.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:center"&gt;*****&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Sophie Summers left Adam, the buzz-cut softie that he was, alone to clean up in the Crash Room. Normally, she would have walked to the Metro with him, as they did at the end of most of her shifts. Today, though, was different. She had her own bit of practice to do, her own band to worry about. Most weeks, they only practiced twice all together. But they had a show, a big one, one where they might finally hit triple digit attendance, and they had to be perfect.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Mal called it a ‘snowball show’. As in, if this show went well, it would all snowball into something bigger. And, maybe. There were a lot of bands in D.C. But most of them gave up, or didn’t have the time, or just never were good enough to get going. Shady Groove, however, could be different. The local circuit was getting bigger here, and they seemed like they had gotten bigger, too. Maybe Sophie was just getting ahead of herself. But she felt good. It all felt close.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Mal and Anna were already in the band room when she arrived, each of them toying with their instruments. Mal seemed to have bought a new guitar tuner, and she was fiddling with it. Anna was setting up her keyboard, a collection of instrument boxes settled beside her.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Hellooo,” said Sophie, the word trailing into sing song. Mal looked up and grinned.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“How was work?” she asked. Mal had her braids jammed under a hat today.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Crazy,” said Sophie. “Awful commute.” Anna laughed. Her hair was down, long, straight, and black.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Did our ghostwriter come up with anything fun?” Sophie rolled her eyes. They had all teased her about trying to credit Adam on their songs. Wendy, yet unseen, had told Sophie that they were not putting a &lt;em&gt;guy &lt;/em&gt;on the credits of their lesbian band’s album. Not as a producer, not as a writer, nada.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“No,” said Sophie, very matter of factly. She found her way to the drum kit and started fiddling with it. Tomorrow, at the show, at Black Cat, she would bring hers. She hated house kits. But it was never worth hauling them around.  “He’s talking about coming tomorrow, though.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I bet he is,” said Mal.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What’s that supposed to mean?” asked Sophie. Mal laughed.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Please tell me this boy knows that you’re a lesbian, Sophie,” she said. Sophie peaked out over her kit. Mal was grinning at her.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“He knows I’m a lesbian,” she said. She knew that Adam liked her. But it had never been anything but endearing, and he had never been anything but the same, shy boy that he had been the first day he met her. Besides, she really wasn’t leading him on. She’d throw in a mention of a girl she was seeing occasionally, just in case he forgot. “Why don’t you guys get teased about your male friends? What’s up with that?” Anna shrugged.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I don’t have any,” she said. “Too pale and too scary.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You just have to get dykier,” said Mal. “If you’re dykier, I’ll stop teasing you about Adam being in love with you.” Sophie snorted.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You’d think the pixie cut and the having sex with women thing would be enough,” she muttered.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You would think that, wouldn’t you,” agreed Mal. Sophie rolled her eyes at her and grinned.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The kit was fine. It wasn’t good, but it was fine. The most unfortunate bit about the drums was just how unwieldy they were. Her bass she could take anywhere. But the drums were different. And since Wendy had bass locked down, she was happy to play the drums. Besides, she did love the drums. The bass was cool, and she liked being out in front of the crowd, playing with everyone, dancing and singing and grinning, but she loved the drums too. The backbone of everything, the workhorse, the core.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Wendy came through the doors to the practice room, and her bass was not slung over her shoulder. Immediately, Sophie knew something was wrong.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“My mom is dying.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:center"&gt;*****&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Adam had the night to himself. Tammy had other friends, real friends, the kind that you didn’t live with and you didn’t pay, and she was spending the night with them, probably drinking in some kind of bar, talking about whatever people talked about on their days away from home. Sports? Movies? Probably not drums, if he had to guess. Tammy was a bit more buttoned up than that.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;He settled in front of the T.V. alone. This was okay. Adam was, in fact, mostly okay with being alone. His whole life, he had spent most of it curating little bits of happiness, little squares of friendship that he cherished, and ignoring the rest of the world. It had been Amy at home, along with his high school best friend Hannah, and it had been his sophomore year T.A. at college, Laura. Each of them had constituted a section of the world, a little one, and the rest had been building his own. Normally, that was just watching something on T.V.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And he liked it that way. It was safe. It was comfortable. Those people, and now Tammy and, even though he was in love with her, Sophie, were the people he felt okay with. And the rest of the time, he felt okay to stare at the T.V. and drift.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;No Seinfeld tonight. That was his and Tammy’s. Instead, he watched some of the trash she refused to watch with him, starting with The O.C. Never mind that The O.C. had a strangely large role in alt music over the last few years, and Tammy loved alt music, or that all of the actors and actresses were gorgeous. Tammy hated it anyway. Her loss. His gain. He started from where he’d previously left off, somewhere in the middle of season one.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;California was so far away. Further away than just about anything could be, at least for someone who had never left the country. It looked so different, too, the palms and the beaches and the &lt;em&gt;space. &lt;/em&gt;Oh, and the sun. There was so much sun in California. Adam Brody was lounging by the pool now, a rarity for him in season one, and Adam let himself slip away. &lt;em&gt;Nice name Adam. Seems like it fits you. You wear it well. &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:center"&gt;*****&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What the fuck are we going to do?” asked Anna in a hushed whisper. The Duchess wasn’t that crowded, not on a Thursday. Mal shook her head.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I don’t know,” she said. “Can we ask her to stay another day?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Absolutely not,” said Sophie. Wendy was in the bathroom, and Sophie was pretty sure she was crying right about now. “We are not asking that girl to stay away from her family.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Do you think she was serious about…” Anna trailed off. Sophie breathed a heavy sigh. It was all crumbling. It always crumbled. The last band, Alesis, fell apart because two of the members started dating and it got messy. The one before that had fallen apart because someone moved. And this one…&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yeah,” said Sophie. “I think she’s out.” And Sophie couldn’t blame her. If her mother had died, if it was her that was flying to Kansas City for a funeral, she wouldn’t be ready to swing up in a band either. Wendy had called it a hiatus, and had told them they could replace her. But Sophie had a sinking feeling she was never coming back. Mal shook her head.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What are we going to do?” she asked.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I don’t know any free bass players here,” said Sophie. “I mean, we can audition people?” Anna nodded. But Mal shook her head.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What about tomorrow?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“We have to cancel,” said Sophie.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“We can’t cancel,” said Mal. “If we cancel Black Cat, we’re not going to get booked anywhere else, and we’re going to have to start from scratch.” Sophie gritted her teeth. It was true. They had cut their teeth for the last year on the local circuit, mostly playing small venues. Black Cat was small, too, but it was a step up. The first step up, and it was the kind that normally led to another.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“We could play as three,” suggested Anna.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“No,” said Mal and Sophie in unison.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Unless you’ve figured out how to play keys and bass at the same time,” said Mal. “We need a fourth.” The three of them sat in silence, Anna teething on a bottle of beer. It felt so callous. It felt so callous for them to be so self interested in this moment, and it hung over the table. Wendy, one of their best friends, was flying out at six in the morning to comfort her father, to comfort herself, because her mother had died. And the three of them were circled in this booth talking about what to do with their band.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I’m going to go check on her,” said Sophie. The other girls nodded, Mal staring at her drink. Sophie took both hers and Wendy’s with her towards the bathroom.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It was mostly empty inside the women’s, which Sophie was grateful for. There was a soft sobbing coming from the stall furthest from the door, and Sophie winced. How long had they left her in here alone?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Wendy?” she called gently. A louder sniff confirmed her suspicions. She eased the stall door open, and found Wendy curled up on the seat. “Hey girl.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Hey,” choked out Wendy.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I brought you your drink,” offered Sophie. Wendy gave a half laugh. Then, as if she was upset at finding something funny right now, she curled tighter.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I don’t know what to do with myself,” she said. “Everything feels so big.” Sophie bit her lip. She wanted to sympathize, but she didn’t know how. What was the answer to someone who had just lost her parent? ‘I’m so sorry?’ ‘It’ll be okay?’ They both felt so insignificant, so untrue, so overwhelmingly stupid and platitudinal, and Sophie couldn’t bring herself to say either of them.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yeah,” she said. “I bet.” Wendy’s body shook.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I’m sorry about tomorrow,” she said. And Sophie, trying her best not to overdo it, shook her head.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Don’t be sorry about it,” she said. “Literally, it doesn’t matter.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Kind of a big break for us,” she said. Black Cat had put out for a show featuring women, for bands completely comprised of women, and it had been the perfect in.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“We’ll get another one,” said Sophie. “These things happen all the time.” And that was a lie, and they both knew it, but that &lt;em&gt;was &lt;/em&gt;the right thing to say. Sophie was the eternal optimist anyway. She could sell that. “We’re so far ahead of schedule for things anyway. We could take a whole year off.” And Wendy laughed. She reached out for the drink. Sophie smiled and gave it to her.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“A whole year off, huh?” she asked. She took a big drink. Sophie tried her best to ignore where they were, and took a drink of her own.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“A whole year off,” she said. “You can go back to Kansas for a while, and then you can come back here and take a break, and then we can all get back to work.” The band would be dead by then. A full year off was a death sentence for a new band. It would kill any and all momentum they had, and Mal and Anna and, yes, Sophie would get bored and find a new project. But that was the wrong thing to say.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Missouri,” said Wendy.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Kansas City is in Missouri, not Kansas,” said Wendy. And Sophie rolled her eyes.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I hate the Midwest,” she said. Then, she added, “Sorry.” Wendy giggled.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Well, I’ve never considered it the Midwest,” she said. Sophie snorted. At least she was smiling a little bit. That was something, wasn’t it? She should be happy with that, shouldn’t she?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“C’mon, babe, lets get you out of the stall,” said Sophie. For a moment, Wendy looked like she might cling to the toilet paper dispenser and make her drag her out. Then, she nodded. Sophie grabbed her hand to steady her as she unfurled from the toilet seat and pulled her out into the open bathroom.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“God, I have to fly,” said Wendy, looking in the mirror. “I have to get on a fucking plane.” Sophie was glad she was worried about something like that, something that felt so small.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Direct?” she asked. Wendy nodded.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I’m not doing any silly connection shenanigans right now,” she said, and Sophie giggled.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She had always liked Wendy. After the problems in the last band, she had sworn off dating any band members, but god, Wendy was hot. Worse still, Wendy had a direct line to make her laugh. There was something about the language she used, the way she slipped into bits of conversation that made Sophie feel like she had read a script in the back of Sophie’s head, and had figured out exactly how to make Sophie’s brain trip. Even now, distraught and lost and drunk, she still did that.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But never mind.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“We’ll take you to the airport,” offered Sophie, but Wendy shook her head.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“No,” she said. “You guys are going to have a big night tomorrow, and I don’t want you tired.” Sophie did her best to put on a poker face. Wendy had to know that they weren’t going to play. Maybe Mal was insisting that they find a fourth, but where? Who the fuck was going to play bass for them right now? So she nodded. And Wendy sniffed out a laugh. “You should still play.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I… want to,” said Sophie, hoping that was enough. But Wendy grimaced.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Short notice,” she said. Sophie, wrapped her arms around Wendy’s waist, pulling her tight. She looked in the mirror, at the smudged glass. Her eyes seemed more tired than they had just two hours ago.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Very,” she said. No use denying it. Wendy looked up with a half smile in the mirror, and, even with the smudged makeup, she looked cute.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I actually have an idea about that,” she said. Sophie raised an eyebrow. Wendy pulled her arms gently away and turned to face her. “You can play bass.” Sophie cocked her head.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“And who’s going to play drums?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="text-align:center"&gt;*****&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Sophie had never called him before this late at night. In fact, Sophie had never called him before period. Adam sat straight up and flipped open his phone.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Sophie?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Hey, Adam, where are you right now?” Sophie sounded drunk. Adam had the pounding, flitting thought that this was some sort of booty call, before remembering that she was, in fact, gay.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“What?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Where. Are. You?” repeated Sophie. Adam looked around.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I’m… at home?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Can I come over for a bit?” It was loud where she was. Drunk. She was definitely drunk.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I guess so,” said Adam.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Great,” said Sophie. “Send me your address. You live in Columbia Heights, right?” Adam nodded. Then, he remembered he was on the phone.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yes,” he said.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“We’re walking,” said Sophie. “Twenty minutes.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And then she hung up. And Adam, his head spinning, jumped up from the couch. Sophie was coming here? &lt;em&gt;We’re walking. &lt;/em&gt;Who’s we? He took a couple of steps forward, into the center of the room. He needed to clean. Thank god Tammy had enough money for a couch, and thank god she had bought a rug.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
